UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# HTML Forms & Input Types — The Complete Guide\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nForms are the primary way users interact with your application. Login pages, registration, search boxes, checkout flows, feedback forms — all are HTML forms at their core. A poorly built form costs companies millions in lost conversions. A well-built form is fast, accessible, and user-friendly.\n\n> **Industry Reality:** At Razorpay, every payment is a form submission. At Zomato, every order starts with a form. Understanding HTML forms deeply — including all input types, validation, accessibility, and submission handling — directly impacts user experience and business outcomes.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Build complete, accessible forms with proper structure\n- Use all HTML5 input types with appropriate attributes\n- Implement client-side validation using HTML5 constraint validation API\n- Handle file uploads, multi-select, and complex form patterns\n- Make forms accessible with proper labels and ARIA\n- Understand form submission mechanics and security basics\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner — Form Structure\n\n```html\n<form action="/api/login" method="POST" novalidate>\n  <label for="email">Email</label>\n  <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required autocomplete="email">\n\n  <label for="password">Password</label>\n  <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required minlength="8">\n\n  <button type="submit">Sign In</button>\n</form>\n```\n\n### Intermediate — All Input Types\n\n```html\n<!-- Text variants -->\n<input type="text"     name="username"   placeholder="Enter username">\n<input type="email"    name="email"      autocomplete="email">\n<input type="password" name="pass"       autocomplete="current-password">\n<input type="search"   name="q"          placeholder="Search courses...">\n<input type="url"      name="website"    placeholder="https://">\n<input type="tel"      name="phone"      pattern="[0-9]{10}">\n\n<!-- Number & range -->\n<input type="number" name="age"    min="18" max="65" step="1">\n<input type="range"  name="volume" min="0"  max="100" value="50">\n\n<!-- Date & time -->\n<input type="date"           name="birthday">\n<input type="time"           name="meeting">\n<input type="datetime-local" name="appointment">\n<input type="month"          name="billing-period">\n<input type="week"           name="sprint">\n\n<!-- Choice -->\n<input type="checkbox" name="agree"  value="yes">\n<input type="radio"    name="gender" value="male">\n<input type="color"    name="theme"  value="#3b82f6">\n\n<!-- File -->\n<input type="file" name="avatar" accept="image/*" multiple>\n\n<!-- Hidden -->\n<input type="hidden" name="csrf_token" value="abc123">\n```\n\n### Advanced — Constraint Validation API\n\n```html\n<form id="signup-form" novalidate>\n  <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required>\n  <span id="email-error" role="alert"></span>\n  <button type="submit">Sign Up</button>\n</form>\n\n<script>\nconst form  = document.getElementById("signup-form");\nconst email = document.getElementById("email");\nconst error = document.getElementById("email-error");\n\nemail.addEventListener("blur", () => {\n  if (email.validity.valueMissing) {\n    error.textContent = "Email is required";\n  } else if (email.validity.typeMismatch) {\n    error.textContent = "Please enter a valid email address";\n  } else {\n    error.textContent = "";\n  }\n});\n\nform.addEventListener("submit", (e) => {\n  e.preventDefault();\n  if (!form.checkValidity()) {\n    // Show all errors\n    form.querySelectorAll(":invalid").forEach(el => el.reportValidity());\n    return;\n  }\n  // Submit\n  const data = new FormData(form);\n  fetch("/api/signup", { method: "POST", body: data });\n});\n</script>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nFORM DATA FLOW\n\nUser fills form\n      ↓\nBrowser validates (if no novalidate)\n      ↓\nUser submits\n      ↓\nPrevention of default (JS)\n      ↓\nClient-side validation\n      ↓\nFormData / JSON serialization\n      ↓\nHTTP POST to server\n      ↓\nServer validation (ALWAYS)\n      ↓\nDatabase / business logic\n      ↓\nHTTP Response (success/error)\n      ↓\nUI feedback to user\n\n\nFORM ATTRIBUTE SUMMARY\n\n<form>\n  action  → URL to submit to (default: current URL)\n  method  → GET (query string) | POST (body)\n  enctype → application/x-www-form-urlencoded (default)\n            multipart/form-data (for file uploads!)\n            text/plain\n  novalidate → Disable browser built-in validation\n  autocomplete → on | off\n\n<input>\n  type        → Defines input behavior and keyboard on mobile\n  name        → Key sent to server (REQUIRED for submission)\n  value       → Current value\n  required    → Must be filled before submit\n  disabled    → Cannot interact, NOT sent to server\n  readonly    → Cannot change, IS sent to server\n  placeholder → Ghost text when empty\n  autocomplete → Hint for browser autofill\n  autofocus   → Focus this field on page load\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax Reference\n\n```html\n<!-- SELECT dropdown -->\n<label for="department">Department</label>\n<select id="department" name="department" required>\n  <option value="">-- Select Department --</option>\n  <optgroup label="Engineering">\n    <option value="frontend">Frontend</option>\n    <option value="backend">Backend</option>\n    <option value="devops">DevOps</option>\n  </optgroup>\n  <optgroup label="Product">\n    <option value="pm">Product Management</option>\n    <option value="design">Design</option>\n  </optgroup>\n</select>\n\n<!-- TEXTAREA -->\n<label for="bio">Bio</label>\n<textarea\n  id="bio"\n  name="bio"\n  rows="5"\n  maxlength="500"\n  placeholder="Tell us about yourself..."\n></textarea>\n\n<!-- FIELDSET — group related fields -->\n<fieldset>\n  <legend>Shipping Address</legend>\n  <label for="street">Street</label>\n  <input type="text" id="street" name="street" required autocomplete="street-address">\n  <label for="city">City</label>\n  <input type="text" id="city" name="city" required autocomplete="address-level2">\n  <label for="pincode">PIN Code</label>\n  <input type="text" id="pincode" name="pincode" pattern="[0-9]{6}" required>\n</fieldset>\n\n<!-- DATALIST — autocomplete suggestions -->\n<label for="city-input">City</label>\n<input type="text" id="city-input" name="city" list="cities-list">\n<datalist id="cities-list">\n  <option value="Bengaluru">\n  <option value="Mumbai">\n  <option value="Hyderabad">\n  <option value="Chennai">\n  <option value="Delhi">\n</datalist>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Login Form (Production-Ready)\n```html\n<form id="login-form" action="/api/auth/login" method="POST" novalidate>\n  <h2>Sign In</h2>\n\n  <div class="field">\n    <label for="email">Email Address</label>\n    <input\n      type="email"\n      id="email"\n      name="email"\n      required\n      autocomplete="email"\n      aria-describedby="email-error"\n      inputmode="email"\n    >\n    <span id="email-error" role="alert" class="error"></span>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class="field">\n    <label for="password">\n      Password\n      <a href="/forgot-password" class="forgot-link">Forgot?</a>\n    </label>\n    <div class="password-wrapper">\n      <input\n        type="password"\n        id="password"\n        name="password"\n        required\n        minlength="8"\n        autocomplete="current-password"\n        aria-describedby="password-error"\n      >\n      <button type="button" aria-label="Show password" id="toggle-password">👁</button>\n    </div>\n    <span id="password-error" role="alert" class="error"></span>\n  </div>\n\n  <label class="checkbox-label">\n    <input type="checkbox" name="remember" value="true">\n    Remember me for 30 days\n  </label>\n\n  <button type="submit" class="btn-primary">Sign In</button>\n\n  <p>No account? <a href="/signup">Create one</a></p>\n</form>\n\n<script>\n  document.getElementById("toggle-password").addEventListener("click", function() {\n    const input = document.getElementById("password");\n    const isPassword = input.type === "password";\n    input.type = isPassword ? "text" : "password";\n    this.setAttribute("aria-label", isPassword ? "Hide password" : "Show password");\n  });\n</script>\n```\n\n### Example 2 — File Upload with Preview\n```html\n<div class="upload-area">\n  <label for="avatar-upload" class="upload-label">\n    <img id="preview" src="/placeholder-avatar.svg" alt="Profile picture preview" width="120" height="120">\n    <span>Click to change photo</span>\n  </label>\n  <input\n    type="file"\n    id="avatar-upload"\n    name="avatar"\n    accept="image/png, image/jpeg, image/webp"\n    class="sr-only"\n  >\n  <p class="hint">JPG, PNG or WebP. Max 2MB.</p>\n</div>\n\n<script>\ndocument.getElementById("avatar-upload").addEventListener("change", function() {\n  const file = this.files[0];\n  if (!file) return;\n\n  if (file.size > 2 * 1024 * 1024) {\n    alert("File too large. Maximum 2MB.");\n    this.value = "";\n    return;\n  }\n\n  const reader = new FileReader();\n  reader.onload = (e) => {\n    document.getElementById("preview").src = e.target.result;\n  };\n  reader.readAsDataURL(file);\n});\n</script>\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Multi-Step Form\n```html\n<form id="multistep" novalidate>\n  <!-- Step indicators -->\n  <div class="steps" aria-label="Form progress">\n    <div class="step active" aria-current="step">1. Personal</div>\n    <div class="step">2. Account</div>\n    <div class="step">3. Confirm</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- Step 1 -->\n  <fieldset class="step-panel active" data-step="1">\n    <legend>Personal Information</legend>\n    <input type="text" name="fullName" placeholder="Full Name" required>\n    <input type="tel"  name="phone" placeholder="Mobile Number" pattern="[0-9]{10}" required>\n    <select name="department" required>\n      <option value="">Select Department</option>\n      <option>Engineering</option>\n      <option>Design</option>\n      <option>Marketing</option>\n    </select>\n    <button type="button" class="next-btn">Next →</button>\n  </fieldset>\n\n  <!-- Step 2 -->\n  <fieldset class="step-panel" data-step="2" hidden>\n    <legend>Account Setup</legend>\n    <input type="email"    name="email"    placeholder="Work Email" required autocomplete="email">\n    <input type="password" name="password" placeholder="Create Password" required minlength="8">\n    <button type="button" class="prev-btn">← Back</button>\n    <button type="button" class="next-btn">Next →</button>\n  </fieldset>\n\n  <!-- Step 3 -->\n  <fieldset class="step-panel" data-step="3" hidden>\n    <legend>Confirm & Submit</legend>\n    <div id="summary"></div>\n    <label>\n      <input type="checkbox" name="terms" required>\n      I agree to the <a href="/terms" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Terms of Service</a>\n    </label>\n    <button type="button" class="prev-btn">← Back</button>\n    <button type="submit">Create Account</button>\n  </fieldset>\n</form>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Registration Form\nBuild a registration form with: full name, email, password (min 8 chars), confirm password, date of birth, department (select with 5 options), profile picture upload, terms checkbox. Apply all validation attributes.\n\n### Exercise 2 — Search Form with Filters\nBuild a course search form with: text search, category filter (multi-select), difficulty radio buttons (Beginner/Intermediate/Advanced), duration range slider, and a Reset button.\n\n### Exercise 3 — Custom Validation\n```javascript\n// Implement custom validation that checks:\n// - Password has at least 1 uppercase, 1 number, 1 special character\n// - Confirm password matches\n// - Email is from allowed domain (@company.com)\n// - Show inline error messages\n// - Disable submit until form is valid\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n| Mistake | Problem | Fix |\n|---------|---------|-----|\n| Missing `name` attribute | Field data not sent to server | Always add `name` to inputs |\n| Using `div` instead of `label` | Not accessible | Use `<label for="id">` |\n| GET method for sensitive data | Password in URL/logs | Use POST for sensitive data |\n| Client-only validation | Easy to bypass | ALWAYS validate on server too |\n| Missing `autocomplete` | Slow user experience | Add appropriate autocomplete values |\n| `disabled` vs `readonly` | Disabled not submitted | Use `readonly` if value should submit |\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n1. **Always pair `<label>` with `<input>`** — use `for`/`id` connection\n2. **Use semantic input types** — triggers right mobile keyboard (email, tel, number)\n3. **Add `autocomplete` attributes** — speeds up form filling significantly\n4. **Group related fields** in `<fieldset>` with `<legend>`\n5. **Never disable the submit button** to show errors — show inline errors instead\n6. **Server-side validation is mandatory** — HTML5 validation can be bypassed\n7. **Use `novalidate` + custom JS** for consistent UX across browsers\n8. **Use `aria-describedby`** to link error messages to inputs\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n**Zomato Checkout:**\n- Delivery address (autocomplete, geolocation)\n- Payment method (radio buttons)\n- Coupon code (text with validation)\n- Special instructions (textarea)\n\n**Company HR Portal:**\n- Employee registration (multi-step with file uploads)\n- Leave application (date range, select)\n- Performance review (ratings, textarea)\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Preparation\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `disabled` and `readonly`?**\n> `disabled`: User cannot interact, field is NOT submitted with the form. `readonly`: User cannot change the value but it IS submitted. Use `readonly` when you want to submit the value but not let users change it.\n\n**Q: How does HTML5 form validation work and how do you customize it?**\n> HTML5 provides built-in constraint validation via attributes (required, minlength, pattern, type). The browser validates on submit. You can use `novalidate` to disable built-in UI and use the Constraint Validation API (element.validity, element.checkValidity(), element.setCustomValidity()) for custom messages and behavior.\n\n**Q: How do you upload files using HTML forms?**\n> Set `method="POST"` and `enctype="multipart/form-data"` on the form. Use `<input type="file">` with `accept` for filtering file types. Server must handle multipart body. For `multiple` files, use `input.files` array in JavaScript.\n\n**Q: What are the security concerns with HTML forms?**\n> Never trust client-side validation — always validate on the server. Protect against CSRF using tokens (hidden field or cookie). Never use GET for sensitive data. Sanitize all input before database insertion to prevent SQL injection and XSS.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What attribute is required for a form field''s data to be submitted?\n2. What is the difference between `<input type="submit">` and `<button type="submit">`?\n3. Which `enctype` value must you use for file uploads?\n4. What is the Constraint Validation API?\n5. How do you make a select field allow multiple selections?\n6. What does the `autocomplete` attribute do?\n7. Why should you use `novalidate` + JavaScript instead of pure HTML5 validation?\n8. What is the `<datalist>` element used for?\n9. How do you link a label to an input without nesting?\n10. What is the difference between `form.submit()` and `form.requestSubmit()`?\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — Form Serializer\n```\nProblem: Write a function that converts a form into a plain JavaScript object.\n\nInput: A <form> element\nOutput: { fieldName: fieldValue, ... }\n\nTest: A form with email, name, and department fields\n```\n\n### Medium — Real-time Form Validator\n```\nProblem: Build a registration form that validates in real-time:\n- Email: valid format, not already taken (mock API check)\n- Password: strength indicator (weak/medium/strong)\n- Confirm password: matches live\n- All fields: show ✓ on valid, ✗ with message on invalid\n- Submit button disabled until all valid\n```\n\n### Hard — Multi-file Upload with Progress\n```\nProblem: Build a drag-and-drop file upload area that:\n- Accepts images only (jpg, png, webp, gif)\n- Max 5 files, max 10MB each\n- Shows thumbnail preview for each file\n- Shows upload progress bar per file\n- Allows removing individual files\n- Submits via fetch with FormData\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — Employee Onboarding Form\n\nBuild a multi-step employee onboarding form:\n- Step 1: Personal (name, email, phone, DOB, address)\n- Step 2: Professional (department, role, start date, manager)\n- Step 3: Documents (photo, ID proof file upload)\n- Step 4: Review and confirm\n- Progress bar showing steps\n- Validate each step before advancing\n- Submit to console.log (simulate API)\n- Success page after submission\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| `<form>` | Container with action, method, enctype |\n| `<input type>` | 20+ types — use the right one |\n| `<label for>` | Always pair with input id — accessibility |\n| `name` attribute | Required for field to be submitted |\n| Validation attrs | required, min, max, minlength, pattern |\n| `novalidate` | Disable built-in browser UI, use custom |\n| File uploads | enctype="multipart/form-data" required |\n| `<fieldset>` | Group related fields logically |\n| Server validation | ALWAYS validate on server — never trust client |\n\nForms are the input layer of every web application. Master them and you control how users interact with your system — securely, efficiently, and accessibly.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l10601';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Semantic HTML5 Elements — Structure with Meaning\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nSemantic HTML is about using the right element for the right purpose. A `<div>` and a `<nav>` can both hold navigation links — but only `<nav>` tells the browser, search engines, and assistive technologies WHAT the content is.\n\nSemantic HTML improves SEO, accessibility, and code maintainability. It is the difference between a page that search engines understand and one they treat as a wall of anonymous divs.\n\n> **Industry Reality:** Google''s ranking algorithm specifically looks for semantic landmarks. Screen reader users navigate by headings and landmarks. React components that output proper semantic HTML rank better and work for users with disabilities. This is not optional in professional development.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Know all HTML5 semantic elements and their correct usage\n- Structure a complete page using only semantic elements\n- Explain the difference between `<section>`, `<article>`, `<aside>`, `<div>`\n- Use text-level semantics correctly\n- Understand how semantic HTML affects SEO and accessibility\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner — Semantic vs Div Soup\n\n```html\n<!-- ❌ DIV SOUP — No meaning -->\n<div class="header">\n  <div class="logo">R-Learn</div>\n  <div class="nav">\n    <div class="nav-item"><a href="/">Home</a></div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<div class="main">\n  <div class="article">...</div>\n</div>\n<div class="footer">...</div>\n\n<!-- ✅ SEMANTIC — Clear meaning -->\n<header>\n  <h1>R-Learn</h1>\n  <nav aria-label="Main">\n    <a href="/">Home</a>\n  </nav>\n</header>\n<main>\n  <article>...</article>\n</main>\n<footer>...</footer>\n```\n\n### Intermediate — Every Semantic Element Explained\n\n**Page Structure Elements:**\n```html\n<header>   <!-- Site header OR section header (can be used multiple times) -->\n<nav>      <!-- Navigation links — main nav, breadcrumbs, pagination -->\n<main>     <!-- PRIMARY content — ONE per page, skip-to-main target -->\n<article>  <!-- Self-contained content (blog post, product card, forum post) -->\n<section>  <!-- Thematic content group — should have a heading -->\n<aside>    <!-- Supplementary content (sidebar, pull quote, ads) -->\n<footer>   <!-- Site footer OR section footer -->\n```\n\n**Content Elements:**\n```html\n<h1>-<h6>      <!-- Heading hierarchy — NEVER skip levels -->\n<p>            <!-- Paragraph of text -->\n<blockquote cite="url">  <!-- Extended quotation from another source -->\n<q>            <!-- Inline quotation -->\n<cite>         <!-- Title of work (book, film, article) -->\n<figure>       <!-- Self-contained referenced content -->\n  <img src="..." alt="...">\n  <figcaption>Caption text</figcaption>\n</figure>\n<time datetime="2024-06-01">June 1, 2024</time>\n<address>      <!-- Contact info for nearest article/body ancestor -->\n<details>      <!-- Disclosure widget (expandable) -->\n  <summary>Click to expand</summary>\n  Hidden content here\n</details>\n<mark>          <!-- Highlighted/relevant text -->\n<abbr title="HyperText Markup Language">HTML</abbr>\n<dfn>          <!-- Term being defined -->\n<kbd>          <!-- Keyboard input -->\n<samp>         <!-- Sample program output -->\n<code>         <!-- Inline code -->\n<pre>          <!-- Preformatted text (preserves whitespace) -->\n<var>          <!-- Mathematical/programming variable -->\n<data value="123">Product SKU 123</data>\n<meter min="0" max="100" value="75">75%</meter>\n<progress max="100" value="60">60%</progress>\n<dialog>       <!-- Modal dialog box -->\n```\n\n### Advanced — Document Outline Algorithm\n\nBrowsers and screen readers build a document outline from your headings. Getting it right is critical:\n\n```html\n<!-- CORRECT heading hierarchy -->\n<h1>R-Learn — Learning Platform</h1>    ← One h1 per page\n\n  <h2>HTML5 Fundamentals</h2>           ← Section heading\n    <h3>Module 1: Web Basics</h3>        ← Subsection\n      <h4>Lesson: DNS Explained</h4>     ← Sub-subsection\n\n  <h2>JavaScript ES6+</h2>              ← Next section\n    <h3>Module 1: Variables</h3>\n\n<!-- WRONG — Skipping levels -->\n<h1>Title</h1>\n<h3>Section</h3>  ← Skipped h2!\n<h2>Next</h2>     ← Out of order!\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nSEMANTIC PAGE STRUCTURE\n\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  <header>                               │\n│   ┌──────────────┐  ┌────────────────┐  │\n│   │ <h1>Logo</h1>│  │    <nav>       │  │\n│   └──────────────┘  └────────────────┘  │\n│  </header>                              │\n├────────────┬────────────────────────────┤\n│            │  <main>                    │\n│  <aside>   │   ┌──────────────────────┐ │\n│            │   │ <article>            │ │\n│  Sidebar   │   │  <header>            │ │\n│  Related   │   │   <h2>Title</h2>     │ │\n│  content   │   │  </header>           │ │\n│            │   │  <section>           │ │\n│            │   │   <h3>Sub</h3>       │ │\n│            │   │  </section>          │ │\n│            │   │  <footer>            │ │\n│            │   │   <time>Date</time>  │ │\n│            │   │  </footer>           │ │\n│            │   └──────────────────────┘ │\n│            │  </main>                   │\n├────────────┴────────────────────────────┤\n│  <footer>                               │\n│   © 2026 R-Learn | Privacy | Terms      │\n│  </footer>                              │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────┘\n\n\nWHEN TO USE EACH ELEMENT\n\narticle vs section vs div:\n\n<article>  → Would make sense on its own (copy/paste to another site)\n            → Examples: blog post, product card, tweet, review, forum reply\n\n<section>  → Thematic group WITHIN the page\n            → Must have a heading\n            → Examples: "About Us", "Features", "FAQ"\n\n<div>      → Generic container, NO semantic meaning\n            → Use ONLY when nothing semantic applies\n            → Examples: styling wrapper, JS hook container\n\n\nDOCUMENT LANDMARKS (screen reader navigation)\n\n<header>   → banner landmark\n<nav>      → navigation landmark\n<main>     → main landmark\n<aside>    → complementary landmark\n<footer>   → contentinfo landmark\n<section>  → region landmark (if has aria-label or aria-labelledby)\n<form>     → form landmark (if has aria-label)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax Reference — Complete Semantic Page\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n  <title>Article Title — R-Learn Blog</title>\n</head>\n<body>\n\n  <!-- Site-wide header -->\n  <header>\n    <a href="/" class="logo">R-Learn</a>\n    <nav aria-label="Main navigation">\n      <ul>\n        <li><a href="/courses" aria-current="page">Courses</a></li>\n        <li><a href="/blog">Blog</a></li>\n        <li><a href="/about">About</a></li>\n      </ul>\n    </nav>\n    <button aria-label="Open search">🔍</button>\n  </header>\n\n  <!-- Breadcrumb navigation -->\n  <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb">\n    <ol>\n      <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>\n      <li><a href="/blog">Blog</a></li>\n      <li aria-current="page">Understanding Flexbox</li>\n    </ol>\n  </nav>\n\n  <div class="container">\n\n    <!-- Main content -->\n    <main id="main-content">\n      <article>\n        <header>\n          <h1>Understanding CSS Flexbox</h1>\n          <p>By <a href="/authors/alice" rel="author">Alice Sharma</a></p>\n          <time datetime="2024-06-01">June 1, 2024</time>\n          <ul class="tags">\n            <li><a href="/tags/css">CSS</a></li>\n            <li><a href="/tags/frontend">Frontend</a></li>\n          </ul>\n        </header>\n\n        <section aria-labelledby="intro-heading">\n          <h2 id="intro-heading">Introduction</h2>\n          <p>Flexbox changed how developers approach layout...</p>\n\n          <figure>\n            <img src="flexbox-diagram.svg" alt="Diagram showing flex container with main and cross axes">\n            <figcaption>Figure 1: The Flexbox axis model</figcaption>\n          </figure>\n        </section>\n\n        <section aria-labelledby="basics-heading">\n          <h2 id="basics-heading">The Basics</h2>\n          <p>Apply <code>display: flex</code> to enable Flexbox...</p>\n          <pre><code>/* Enable Flexbox */\n.container { display: flex; }</code></pre>\n        </section>\n\n        <aside aria-label="Quick tip">\n          <p><mark>Tip:</mark> Use <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>C</kbd> to inspect elements in DevTools.</p>\n        </aside>\n\n        <footer>\n          <p>Updated: <time datetime="2024-06-15">June 15, 2024</time></p>\n          <address>\n            Questions? <a href="mailto:blog@rlearn.com">blog@rlearn.com</a>\n          </address>\n        </footer>\n      </article>\n\n      <!-- Related articles -->\n      <section aria-labelledby="related-heading">\n        <h2 id="related-heading">Related Articles</h2>\n        <article>\n          <h3><a href="/blog/css-grid">CSS Grid Complete Guide</a></h3>\n          <p>Mastering two-dimensional layouts...</p>\n        </article>\n      </section>\n    </main>\n\n    <!-- Sidebar -->\n    <aside aria-label="Sidebar">\n      <section aria-labelledby="toc-heading">\n        <h2 id="toc-heading">In This Article</h2>\n        <nav aria-label="Table of contents">\n          <ol>\n            <li><a href="#intro-heading">Introduction</a></li>\n            <li><a href="#basics-heading">The Basics</a></li>\n          </ol>\n        </nav>\n      </section>\n    </aside>\n\n  </div>\n\n  <!-- Site-wide footer -->\n  <footer>\n    <nav aria-label="Footer navigation">\n      <a href="/privacy">Privacy Policy</a>\n      <a href="/terms">Terms</a>\n      <a href="/sitemap">Sitemap</a>\n    </nav>\n    <p><small>&copy; 2024 R-Learn. All rights reserved.</small></p>\n  </footer>\n\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Refactor to Semantic HTML\nTake this div-soup and convert to proper semantic HTML:\n```html\n<div class="page">\n  <div class="top-bar">...</div>\n  <div class="content">\n    <div class="post">...</div>\n    <div class="sidebar">...</div>\n  </div>\n  <div class="bottom">...</div>\n</div>\n```\n\n### Exercise 2 — Blog Post Markup\nMark up a blog post with: author, date, hero image with caption, 3 sections each with subheadings, a code example, a blockquote, related articles section, and a footer with tags.\n\n### Exercise 3 — `<details>` FAQ\nBuild a FAQ section using `<details>` and `<summary>` for 5 questions. Add CSS to animate the opening with `transition`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Common Mistakes\n\n| Mistake | Fix |\n|---------|-----|\n| Multiple `<h1>` per page | One `<h1>` per page (the main title) |\n| Skipping heading levels (h1→h3) | Always go in order: h1→h2→h3 |\n| `<section>` without heading | Either add heading or use `<div>` |\n| `<article>` for UI components | `<article>` for standalone content only |\n| `<div>` inside `<p>` | `<p>` cannot contain block elements |\n| Putting `<main>` inside `<article>` | `<main>` is top-level only |\n\n---\n\n## 8. Best Practices\n\n1. **One `<h1>` per page** — the page''s primary title\n2. **Never skip heading levels** — h1→h2→h3 always in order\n3. **`<article>` content should stand alone** — if you can copy it to another page and it makes sense, it''s an article\n4. **Label your `<nav>` elements** — `aria-label="Main navigation"` distinguishes multiple navs\n5. **Use `<figure>` + `<figcaption>`** for images with captions\n6. **Add `aria-label` to `<section>`** if it would help screen reader navigation\n7. **Skip navigation link** — `<a href="#main-content" class="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>` for keyboard users\n\n---\n\n## 9. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `<article>` and `<section>`?**\n> `<article>` is for self-contained, independently distributable content (a blog post, product review, tweet). `<section>` is for thematic grouping of content within a page. An article can contain sections; a section can contain articles.\n\n**Q: How does semantic HTML help SEO?**\n> Search engines understand content hierarchy through headings (h1-h6) and landmarks (header, nav, main, article, footer). Proper semantics help Google understand what the page is about, identify the main content, and extract structured data. Pages with good semantics rank better.\n\n**Q: When should you use `<div>` over semantic elements?**\n> Only when no semantic element fits. `<div>` is for visual grouping with CSS or JavaScript hooks. If an element has meaning (navigation, sidebar, article content), use the semantic element. The test: "Does this element change what the content MEANS?" If yes, use semantic; if no, use div.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Knowledge Check\n\n1. How many `<main>` elements should a page have?\n2. What is the difference between `<header>` and `<head>`?\n3. When should you use `<article>` vs `<section>`?\n4. What element marks up keyboard input like Ctrl+C?\n5. What is the purpose of `<details>` and `<summary>`?\n6. Why does `<section>` need a heading?\n7. What landmark role does `<aside>` map to?\n8. How do you distinguish multiple `<nav>` elements for accessibility?\n9. What does `<time datetime="2024-06-01">` add that plain text doesn''t?\n10. What is the `<dialog>` element used for?\n\n---\n\n## 11. Coding Challenge\n\n### Medium — Semantic News Homepage\nBuild a news website homepage with:\n- Header with logo and nav\n- Breaking news banner (use `<aside role="alert">`)\n- Featured article with figure/figcaption\n- Three-column grid of article summaries\n- Sidebar with trending topics and newsletter signup\n- Footer with site links and contact\n- Zero `<div>` tags unless absolutely necessary\n\n---\n\n## 12. Lesson Summary\n\n| Element | Purpose | Use When |\n|---------|---------|----------|\n| `<header>` | Page/section header | Logo, title, nav at top |\n| `<nav>` | Navigation links | Menus, breadcrumbs, pagination |\n| `<main>` | Primary content | The unique content of this page |\n| `<article>` | Self-contained content | Blog posts, cards, reviews |\n| `<section>` | Thematic grouping | Page sections with headings |\n| `<aside>` | Supplementary | Sidebar, pull quotes, ads |\n| `<footer>` | Page/section footer | Copyright, contact, links |\n| `<figure>` | Referenced content | Images with captions |\n| `<time>` | Date/time | Always use with datetime attribute |\n\nSemantic HTML is the foundation of accessible, SEO-friendly web development. Use the right element for the right job — not just for browsers, but for the humans who depend on assistive technology.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l10701';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Accessibility & ARIA — Building for Everyone\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nOver 1 billion people worldwide have some form of disability. Accessibility (a11y) means building websites that work for everyone — including users who are blind, deaf, have motor disabilities, or cognitive differences. Beyond ethics, accessibility is often legally required (WCAG 2.1 AA compliance is mandated in many countries).\n\n> **Industry Reality:** Microsoft, Google, and major Indian companies have accessibility mandates. The Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) are a legal requirement in the EU, US (ADA), and increasingly in India. A11y issues in production get escalated — and fixing them post-launch is 10× more expensive than building them in.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Understand WCAG 2.1 guidelines (perceivable, operable, understandable, robust)\n- Use ARIA roles, properties, and states correctly\n- Make all interactive elements keyboard-accessible\n- Write accessible forms, images, navigation, and dynamic content\n- Test accessibility with screen readers and automated tools\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner — The Four Principles (POUR)\n\n```\nPerceivable   → Information must be available to all senses\n                Alt text for images, captions for video, sufficient color contrast\n\nOperable      → UI must be navigable without a mouse\n                All interactive elements keyboard-accessible, no time traps\n\nUnderstandable → Content must be readable and predictable\n                Clear language, consistent navigation, error descriptions\n\nRobust        → Content works with current and future assistive technologies\n                Valid HTML, ARIA used correctly\n```\n\n### Intermediate — ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications)\n\nARIA adds semantic meaning to elements that HTML alone cannot express:\n\n```html\n<!-- ARIA Roles — What is this element? -->\n<div role="button" tabindex="0">Custom Button</div>\n<div role="navigation" aria-label="Main nav">...</div>\n<div role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="dialog-title">\n  <h2 id="dialog-title">Confirm Delete</h2>\n</div>\n<div role="alert">⚠ Error: Invalid email address</div>\n<div role="status" aria-live="polite">Course saved successfully</div>\n\n<!-- ARIA Properties — Describe the element -->\n<button aria-label="Close dialog">✕</button>\n<input aria-describedby="hint-text">\n<p id="hint-text">Password must be 8+ characters</p>\n<img src="chart.png" aria-labelledby="chart-desc">\n<p id="chart-desc">Bar chart showing Q3 revenue of ₹4.2M</p>\n\n<!-- ARIA States — Current condition -->\n<button aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="dropdown-menu">Menu</button>\n<ul id="dropdown-menu" aria-hidden="true">...</ul>\n\n<input type="checkbox" aria-checked="true">\n<li role="option" aria-selected="true">React</li>\n<div aria-busy="true" aria-label="Loading courses...">⏳</div>\n<input aria-invalid="true" aria-errormessage="email-error">\n<span id="email-error" role="alert">Invalid email format</span>\n```\n\n### Advanced — Live Regions and Focus Management\n\n```html\n<!-- Live regions: announce dynamic content to screen readers -->\n\n<!-- polite: waits for user to finish current action -->\n<div aria-live="polite" aria-atomic="true" id="status-message"></div>\n\n<!-- assertive: interrupts immediately (use for errors/urgent) -->\n<div aria-live="assertive" id="error-message"></div>\n\n<!-- role="status" (polite) and role="alert" (assertive) are shortcuts -->\n<p role="status">Form saved automatically</p>\n<p role="alert">Session expiring in 2 minutes</p>\n\n<!-- Focus management for modal dialogs -->\n<script>\nfunction openModal() {\n  const modal = document.getElementById("dialog");\n  modal.removeAttribute("hidden");\n  modal.setAttribute("aria-hidden", "false");\n\n  // Trap focus inside modal\n  const focusable = modal.querySelectorAll(\n    ''button, [href], input, select, textarea, [tabindex]:not([tabindex="-1"])''\n  );\n  focusable[0].focus();\n\n  // When modal closes, return focus to trigger\n  modal.addEventListener("keydown", (e) => {\n    if (e.key === "Escape") closeModal();\n    if (e.key === "Tab") trapFocus(e, focusable);\n  });\n}\n\nfunction closeModal() {\n  const modal = document.getElementById("dialog");\n  modal.setAttribute("hidden", "");\n  modal.setAttribute("aria-hidden", "true");\n  document.getElementById("open-modal-btn").focus(); // Return focus\n}\n</script>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nWCAG CONFORMANCE LEVELS\n\nLevel A    → Minimum accessibility (must do)\n  - Alt text for images\n  - Keyboard navigation\n  - Form labels\n\nLevel AA   → Standard (industry target, legally required)\n  - Color contrast ratio ≥ 4.5:1 for text\n  - Visible focus indicators\n  - Error identification\n  - Consistent navigation\n\nLevel AAA  → Enhanced (aspirational)\n  - Contrast ratio ≥ 7:1\n  - Sign language for video\n  - No timing requirements\n\n\nARIA DECISION TREE\n\nDo you need to add accessibility?\n         │\n         ▼\nIs there a semantic HTML element?\n    YES ─────────────────> Use it!  <button> not <div role="button">\n         │\n         NO\n         │\n         ▼\nAdd role= to define what it is\nAdd aria-label/labelledby for naming\nAdd aria-expanded/checked/selected for state\nManage focus programmatically\nHandle keyboard events\n\n\nKEYBOARD NAVIGATION RULES\n\nEnter / Space  → Activate button, submit form, check checkbox\nArrow keys     → Navigate within widget (menu, tabs, listbox)\nTab            → Move to next focusable element\nShift+Tab      → Move to previous focusable element\nEscape         → Close dialog, menu, tooltip\nHome/End       → First/last item in list\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Accessible Navigation\n```html\n<!-- Skip to main content link (appears on keyboard focus) -->\n<a href="#main-content" class="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>\n\n<!-- The class makes it visible only on focus -->\n<style>\n.skip-link {\n  position: absolute;\n  top: -100%;\n  left: 0;\n  background: #1e40af;\n  color: white;\n  padding: 0.5rem 1rem;\n  text-decoration: none;\n  z-index: 999;\n}\n.skip-link:focus {\n  top: 0;  /* Visible when focused --\n}\n</style>\n\n<nav aria-label="Main navigation">\n  <ul role="list">\n    <li><a href="/" aria-current="page">Home</a></li>\n    <li><a href="/courses">Courses</a></li>\n    <li>\n      <!-- Dropdown button -->\n      <button\n        aria-expanded="false"\n        aria-haspopup="true"\n        aria-controls="resources-dropdown"\n        id="resources-btn"\n      >\n        Resources\n      </button>\n      <ul id="resources-dropdown" role="list" hidden>\n        <li><a href="/docs">Documentation</a></li>\n        <li><a href="/blog">Blog</a></li>\n      </ul>\n    </li>\n  </ul>\n</nav>\n\n<main id="main-content">\n  <!-- Page content -->\n</main>\n\n<script>\nconst btn = document.getElementById("resources-btn");\nconst menu = document.getElementById("resources-dropdown");\n\nbtn.addEventListener("click", () => {\n  const expanded = btn.getAttribute("aria-expanded") === "true";\n  btn.setAttribute("aria-expanded", !expanded);\n  menu.hidden = expanded;\n});\n</script>\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Accessible Form with Error Handling\n```html\n<form novalidate aria-labelledby="form-heading">\n  <h2 id="form-heading">Create Account</h2>\n\n  <!-- Error summary (shown after failed submit) -->\n  <div id="error-summary" role="alert" hidden>\n    <h3>Please fix the following errors:</h3>\n    <ul id="error-list"></ul>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class="field">\n    <label for="name">Full Name <span aria-hidden="true">*</span></label>\n    <input\n      type="text"\n      id="name"\n      name="name"\n      required\n      aria-required="true"\n      aria-describedby="name-error"\n      autocomplete="name"\n    >\n    <span id="name-error" role="alert" hidden>Please enter your full name</span>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class="field">\n    <label for="email">Email Address <span aria-hidden="true">*</span></label>\n    <input\n      type="email"\n      id="email"\n      name="email"\n      required\n      aria-required="true"\n      aria-describedby="email-hint email-error"\n      autocomplete="email"\n    >\n    <p id="email-hint" class="hint">We will send a verification link to this address.</p>\n    <span id="email-error" role="alert" hidden>Please enter a valid email address</span>\n  </div>\n\n  <button type="submit">Create Account</button>\n</form>\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Accessible Data Table\n```html\n<table>\n  <caption>Course Enrollment Summary — Q2 2024</caption>\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th scope="col">Course</th>\n      <th scope="col">Enrolled</th>\n      <th scope="col">Completed</th>\n      <th scope="col" aria-sort="descending">Completion Rate</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <th scope="row">HTML5 Fundamentals</th>\n      <td>245</td>\n      <td>198</td>\n      <td>81%</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th scope="row">JavaScript ES6+</th>\n      <td>312</td>\n      <td>187</td>\n      <td>60%</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n  <tfoot>\n    <tr>\n      <th scope="row">Total</th>\n      <td>557</td>\n      <td>385</td>\n      <td>69%</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tfoot>\n</table>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise — Accessible Modal Dialog\nBuild a modal dialog that:\n- Opens when a button is clicked\n- Traps focus inside when open\n- Closes with Escape key\n- Returns focus to trigger button on close\n- Has proper ARIA attributes (role="dialog", aria-modal, aria-labelledby)\n- Background content gets aria-hidden="true" when modal is open\n\n---\n\n## 7. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the first rule of ARIA?**\n> Don''t use ARIA if you can use a native HTML element. `<button>` is better than `<div role="button">` because native elements have built-in keyboard behavior, focus management, and semantics. ARIA is for cases where native HTML is insufficient.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `aria-label` and `aria-labelledby`?**\n> `aria-label` provides a direct string label. `aria-labelledby` references another element''s text by ID. Use `aria-labelledby` when the label text is already visible on the page (better for internationalization). Use `aria-label` when there is no visible label text (like icon-only buttons).\n\n**Q: What are ARIA live regions and when do you use them?**\n> Live regions announce dynamic content changes to screen readers without the user navigating to the updated area. `aria-live="polite"` waits for idle before announcing (status messages, auto-saves). `aria-live="assertive"` interrupts immediately (error messages, urgent notifications).\n\n---\n\n## 8. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What do the four letters in POUR stand for?\n2. What color contrast ratio is required for WCAG AA compliance?\n3. What is the first rule of ARIA?\n4. How do you announce dynamic content changes to screen readers?\n5. What is a skip navigation link and who benefits from it?\n6. What is the difference between `aria-hidden` and `hidden`?\n7. When should you use `aria-live="assertive"` vs `aria-live="polite"`?\n8. How do you trap focus inside a modal dialog?\n9. What attribute announces that a button opens a dropdown?\n10. What WCAG level is typically required for legal compliance?\n\n---\n\n## 9. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| WCAG POUR | Perceivable, Operable, Understandable, Robust |\n| ARIA Rule 1 | Use native HTML first, ARIA second |\n| aria-label | Direct string label for element |\n| aria-labelledby | Reference visible text as label |\n| aria-describedby | Reference additional description |\n| aria-live | Announce dynamic content changes |\n| Focus management | Modals trap focus; return on close |\n| Skip links | Allow keyboard users to skip nav |\n| tabindex="0" | Make custom element focusable |\n| tabindex="-1" | Focusable via JS only |\n\nAccessibility is not a feature you add — it is a quality of how you build. An accessible product works better for everyone, not just users with disabilities. Build with accessibility from the start.', 30, 1)
