UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# SEO Fundamentals for Developers\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nSEO (Search Engine Optimization) is the practice of making your website appear higher in search results. For developers, SEO is largely about writing clean, semantic, fast HTML — not marketing tricks.\n\nGood developer SEO means: correct meta tags, semantic structure, fast performance, structured data, and proper URL patterns. These decisions, made in code, directly determine whether your product gets organic traffic.\n\n> **Business Impact:** Zomato, Naukri, and Urban Company get millions of visitors monthly from search engines — for free. Poor developer SEO decisions (missing meta tags, slow pages, bad URL structure) can cost millions in lost traffic. This is directly the developer''s responsibility.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\n- Write all essential meta tags for SEO\n- Implement Open Graph and Twitter Card meta tags\n- Use structured data (JSON-LD) for rich results\n- Understand technical SEO: canonical URLs, robots, sitemaps\n- Optimize Core Web Vitals from an HTML perspective\n\n---\n\n## 3. Core SEO Concepts\n\n### On-Page SEO Elements\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <!-- Core SEO -->\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n  <title>HTML5 Fundamentals Course — R-Learn | Learn Web Development</title>\n  <!-- 50-60 chars: Primary keyword + Brand -->\n\n  <meta name="description" content="Master HTML5 from scratch. 12 modules, 40 lessons, hands-on projects. Start for free today.">\n  <!-- 150-160 chars: Compelling description with call to action -->\n\n  <meta name="robots" content="index, follow">\n  <!-- index/noindex: Should Google index this page? -->\n  <!-- follow/nofollow: Should Google follow links? -->\n\n  <!-- Canonical: Prevents duplicate content penalty -->\n  <link rel="canonical" href="https://rlearn.com/courses/html5">\n\n  <!-- Language alternates (for multi-language sites) -->\n  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="en" href="https://rlearn.com/courses/html5">\n  <link rel="alternate" hreflang="hi" href="https://rlearn.com/hi/courses/html5">\n\n  <!-- Open Graph (Facebook, LinkedIn, WhatsApp) -->\n  <meta property="og:type"        content="website">\n  <meta property="og:title"       content="HTML5 Fundamentals — R-Learn">\n  <meta property="og:description" content="Master HTML5 from scratch. 12 modules, hands-on projects.">\n  <meta property="og:image"       content="https://rlearn.com/og/html5-course.jpg">\n  <meta property="og:url"         content="https://rlearn.com/courses/html5">\n  <meta property="og:site_name"   content="R-Learn">\n  <meta property="og:locale"      content="en_IN">\n\n  <!-- Twitter Card -->\n  <meta name="twitter:card"        content="summary_large_image">\n  <meta name="twitter:site"        content="@rlearn">\n  <meta name="twitter:title"       content="HTML5 Fundamentals — R-Learn">\n  <meta name="twitter:description" content="Master HTML5 from scratch.">\n  <meta name="twitter:image"       content="https://rlearn.com/og/html5-course.jpg">\n</head>\n```\n\n### Structured Data (JSON-LD)\n```html\n<!-- Course structured data for rich results in Google -->\n<script type="application/ld+json">\n{\n  "@context": "https://schema.org",\n  "@type": "Course",\n  "name": "HTML5 Fundamentals",\n  "description": "Master HTML5 from scratch with 12 modules and hands-on projects",\n  "provider": {\n    "@type": "Organization",\n    "name": "R-Learn",\n    "sameAs": "https://rlearn.com"\n  },\n  "educationalLevel": "Beginner",\n  "coursePrerequisites": "None",\n  "offers": {\n    "@type": "Offer",\n    "price": "0",\n    "priceCurrency": "INR",\n    "availability": "https://schema.org/InStock"\n  },\n  "aggregateRating": {\n    "@type": "AggregateRating",\n    "ratingValue": "4.8",\n    "reviewCount": "1247",\n    "bestRating": "5"\n  }\n}\n</script>\n\n<!-- Breadcrumb structured data -->\n<script type="application/ld+json">\n{\n  "@context": "https://schema.org",\n  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",\n  "itemListElement": [\n    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://rlearn.com" },\n    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Courses", "item": "https://rlearn.com/courses" },\n    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "HTML5 Fundamentals" }\n  ]\n}\n</script>\n\n<!-- FAQ structured data -->\n<script type="application/ld+json">\n{\n  "@context": "https://schema.org",\n  "@type": "FAQPage",\n  "mainEntity": [\n    {\n      "@type": "Question",\n      "name": "Is this course free?",\n      "acceptedAnswer": {\n        "@type": "Answer",\n        "text": "Yes, all R-Learn courses are free for company employees."\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}\n</script>\n```\n\n### Technical SEO: robots.txt and Sitemap\n```\n# robots.txt (at https://rlearn.com/robots.txt)\nUser-agent: *\nAllow: /courses/\nAllow: /blog/\nDisallow: /admin/\nDisallow: /api/\nDisallow: /private/\n\nSitemap: https://rlearn.com/sitemap.xml\n```\n\n```xml\n<!-- sitemap.xml -->\n<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n<urlset xmlns="http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9">\n  <url>\n    <loc>https://rlearn.com/courses/html5</loc>\n    <lastmod>2024-06-01</lastmod>\n    <changefreq>monthly</changefreq>\n    <priority>0.8</priority>\n  </url>\n</urlset>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Core Web Vitals (Google Ranking Factors)\n\n```\nLCP (Largest Contentful Paint) — Loading\n  Good: < 2.5s\n  Fix: Preload hero image, fast server, CDN\n  <link rel="preload" as="image" href="hero.jpg">\n\nFID (First Input Delay) — Interactivity  \n  Good: < 100ms\n  Fix: Reduce JS execution time, defer non-critical scripts\n\nCLS (Cumulative Layout Shift) — Visual Stability\n  Good: < 0.1\n  Fix: Always set width/height on images and video\n  <img src="hero.jpg" width="1200" height="600" alt="...">\n  Never inject content above existing content\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is a canonical URL and why is it important?**\n> A canonical URL (`<link rel="canonical">`) tells search engines which URL is the authoritative version when duplicate or similar content exists at multiple URLs (e.g., with/without www, with/without trailing slash, paginated versions). Without canonical tags, Google may penalize duplicate content or split ranking signals across multiple URLs.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `index/noindex` and `follow/nofollow` in robots meta?**\n> `index` allows Google to show the page in search results; `noindex` excludes it. `follow` allows Google to follow links on the page to discover other pages; `nofollow` tells Google not to follow links. They are independent: `noindex, follow` means "don''t show this page in results but do follow its links."\n\n**Q: What is structured data and why do developers need to implement it?**\n> Structured data (JSON-LD, Microdata, RDFa) is code that tells search engines specifically what your content means. It enables "rich results" in Google — star ratings, FAQs, event dates, breadcrumbs directly in search results. Rich results get significantly higher click-through rates than standard results.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Knowledge Check\n\n1. How long should a title tag be for SEO?\n2. What is the purpose of the meta description?\n3. What does `<link rel="canonical">` do?\n4. What are Open Graph tags used for?\n5. What is JSON-LD structured data?\n6. What does robots.txt control?\n7. What are Core Web Vitals?\n8. Why must images have explicit width and height for SEO?\n9. What is an XML sitemap?\n10. What does `hreflang` do?\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Element | SEO Impact |\n|---------|------------|\n| `<title>` | #1 SEO factor — 50-60 chars |\n| `<meta description>` | Click-through rate — 150-160 chars |\n| `<h1>` | Primary keyword signal — one per page |\n| `<link rel="canonical">` | Prevent duplicate content penalty |\n| JSON-LD | Enable rich results in Google |\n| Image alt text | Image search ranking, accessibility |\n| Core Web Vitals | Direct Google ranking factor |\n| robots.txt | Control crawler access |\n\nDevelopers control SEO outcomes through code. Clean semantic HTML, fast performance, and proper meta tags are developer responsibilities that directly impact organic traffic and business growth.', 25, 1)
